qas.question: Who is Philadelphia's greatest architect of the later 19th century?
When did building begin on the Philadelphia CIty Hall?

context: In the first decades of the 19th century, Federal architecture and Greek Revival architecture were dominated by Philadelphia architects such as <a0_0>Benjamin Latrobe, William Strickland, John Haviland, John Notman, Thomas U. Walter, and Samuel Sloan<a0_0/>. <a1_0>Frank Furness<a1_0/> is considered Philadelphia's greatest architect of the second half of the 19th century, but his contemporaries included John McArthur, Jr., Addison Hutton, Wilson Eyre, the Wilson Brothers, and Horace Trumbauer. In <a2_0>1871<a2_0/>, construction began on the Second Empire-style Philadelphia City Hall. The <a3_0>Philadelphia Historical Commission<a3_0/> was created in 1955 to preserve the cultural and architectural history of the city. The commission maintains the <a4_0>Philadelphia Register of Historic Places<a4_0/>, adding historic buildings, structures, sites, objects and districts as it sees fit.
